<br>
You just dont get it.<br>
<br>
When they asked me to be the Primary President I laughed and asked if they were kidding.  You are just seeing this in a different perspective. - Shirene <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#b9a1d0><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/breligiousdebate60574.showUserPublicProfile?gid=mamagadfly>MamaGadfly</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 362<br> <font color=#3333ff>(4/22/03 6:44 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/freligiousdebate60574frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=179.topic&index=62>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_mad.gif" align=absmiddle>  No really, it's being on top that's the burden!?!?!</span><hr size=1> No, really it seems as though you don't get it either Shirene. This sounds alot like the sexist arguments of those who don't want women &quot;burdened&quot; with the stress of meetings, working late, balancing work/life priorities etc. It is a fact that in every xian sect, men hold positions of power while women have generally better attendance and stay in their places as breeders, daycare providers, Sunday school teachers. <br>
